\begin_layout Enumerate
Two of Maxwell's equations in vacuum are 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{E}=-\frac{\partial\vec{B}}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{B}=\frac{1}{c^{2}}\frac{\partial\vec{E}}{\partial t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the speed of light.
 Take the curl of both sides of the second equation to obtain a PDE in 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 alone.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the interior of a hollow metal container, where the boundary conditions
 are that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 is perpendicular to the metal at the surface (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\vec{E}\times\vec{n}\right|_{\partial\Omega}=0$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a perfect conductor, any nonzero component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 parallel to the surface would generate an infinite current parallel to
 the surface, in which charges instantaneously rearrang to cancel the field.
 For a real conductor with finite conductivity, matters are more complicated
 because we must consider what the fields do inside the conductor, but a
 perfect conductor is a good approximation at microwave and lower frequencies
 where the penetration of the field into the conductor (the 
\emph on
skin depth
\emph default
) is much smaller than the wavelength of light.
\end_layout

\end_inset

